 ever. Bios and profiles abound. =E2=80=9C60 Minutes=E2=80=9D did a feature=
 on him just last year. Anything you want to know about Mr. Roger N.M.I. Fe=
derer =E2=80=94 his background, his home town of Basel, Switzerland, his pa=
rents=E2=80=99 sane and unexploitative support of his talent, his junior te=
nnis career, his early problems with fragility and temper, his beloved juni=
or coach, how that coach=E2=80=99s accidental death in 2002 both shattered =
and annealed Federer and helped make him what he now is, Federer=E2=80=99s =
39 career singles titles, his eight Grand Slams, his unusually steady and m=
ature commitment to the girlfriend who travels with him (which on the men=
=E2=80=99s tour is rare) and handles his affairs (which on the men=E2=80=99=
s tour is unheard of), his old-school stoicism and mental toughness and goo=
d sportsmanship and evident overall decency and thoughtfulness and charitab=
le largess =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s all just a Google search away. Knock your=
self out.
=E2=80=A6before writing that what he wanted to write about was the transcen=
dent experience of watching Federer play:
This present article is more about a spectator=E2=80=99s experience of Fede=
rer, and its context. The specific thesis here is that if you=E2=80=99ve ne=
ver seen the young man play live, and then do, in person, on the sacred gra=
ss of Wimbledon, through the literally withering heat and then wind and rai=
n of the =E2=80=9906 fortnight, then you are apt to have what one of the to=
urnament=E2=80=99s press bus drivers describes as a =E2=80=9Cbloody near-re=
ligious experience.=E2=80=9D It may be tempting, at first, to hear a phrase=
 like this as just one more of the overheated tropes that people resort to =
to describe the feeling of Federer Moments. But the driver=E2=80=99s phrase=
 turns out to be true =E2=80=94 literally, for an instant ecstatically =E2=
=80=94 though it takes some time and serious watching to see this truth eme=
rge.
Understanding DFW=E2=80=99s Big Question, do you see why he asks the specif=
ic sub-questions he does in each of these profiles?
I guess the point here being that do you see what I mean w/r/t answers just=
 not being that interesting and the questions you ask shaping your reality?=
 No one else would write Federer like DFW did. McPhee, writing about a tenn=
is match in one of his most famous essays, Levels of the Game [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/68e797a6-0ee4-4d36-9196-21dbdf4c38b0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], writes an entirely diffe=
rent piece! It=E2=80=99s analytical and structured where DFW=E2=80=99s is s=
ubjective and ecstatic. They are both excellent. They both answer entirely =
different questions.
In a New Yorker  [ https://substack.com/redirect/d3ffb6bd-f4f4-48a4-af1f-96=
6d52307928?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]profile on Wallace [ https://substack.com/redirect/d3ffb6bd-f4f4-48a4-a=
f1f-966d52307928?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ] a year after his death by suicide, D.T. Max describes the partic=
ular tragedy of losing a genius mid-question:
The sadness over Wallace=E2=80=99s death was also connected to a feeling th=
at, for all his outpouring of words, he died with his work incomplete. Wall=
ace, at least, never felt that he had hit his target. His goal had been to =
show readers how to live a fulfilled, meaningful life. =E2=80=9CFiction=E2=
=80=99s about what it is to be a fucking human being,=E2=80=9D he once said=
=2E
I don=E2=80=99t know. One of the things it is to be a human being is to pur=
sue a question so Big that you could pursue it for a Bryan Johnson Lifetime=
 and never get your answer.
How many total lives have been spent questioning the meaning of life? Are w=
e closer to an answer? Is there an answer?
Most of us spend most of our working lives trying to find specific answers =
to other peoples=E2=80=99 questions. No two ways about it: that skill is be=
coming commoditized [ https://substack.com/redirect/01a189c3-c223-4ca4-a450=
-c6aae85c6d9b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ].
There has never been a better time, however, to be someone with a burning q=
uestion to answer.
Pinning down your question isn=E2=80=99t easy =E2=80=93 I=E2=80=99m still w=
restling with mine =E2=80=93 but it=E2=80=99s worth every second you can gi=
ve to it. It will shape everything else you do.
Take some time this weekend =E2=80=93 better yet, play hooky, take a snow d=
ay or a sick day =E2=80=93 and just think about the question you=E2=80=99d =
be happy spending a decade or six trying to answer. It=E2=80=99ll light up =
your world more than any answer could.
Long questions, short answers.
Thanks to Claude for editing and to Vanta [ https://substack.com/redirect/7=
87662db-9766-447e-8c9a-9294ed250e80?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for supporting Not Boring. Go support them so=
 I can keep asking questions.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with the Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

