px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;min-width: 10px=
;"><span>Patrick named the episode &#8220;</span><em>The Talent Whisperer,<=
/em><span>&#8221;</span><em> </em><span>and what becomes clear throughout t=
he conversation is that Graham has crafted a successful career and life by =
asking the question: &#8220;How do you see someone, including yourself, cle=
arly?&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);=
line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;min-width: 10px;">Graham has made an art =
of understanding people &#8211; Patrick introduced him by saying that his &=
#8220;reputation was as the most discerning people picker on Wall Street&#8=
221; &#8211; and in his essay, he writes that one of the best ways to do th=
at is to see what kinds of questions they ask:</p><blockquote style=3D"bord=
er-left: 4px solid #0c2427;margin: 20px 0;padding: 0;"><p style=3D"margin: =
0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);margin-left: 20px;line-height: 26px;font-si=
ze: 16px;min-width: 10px;"><em><span>It also helps to have the candidate yo=
u&#8217;re trying to see clearly ask you questions. Questions have very hig=
h signal value compared to most anything else you can get from a candidate&=
#8230; I write down each question and sometimes respond with &#8220;I&#8217=
;ll answer, but first I&#8217;m curious, why did you ask that?&#8221; </spa=
n><strong>I&#8217;m looking for the felt sense of a &#8220;hungry mind&#822=
1; based on the way their questions flow. That&#8217;s very hard to fake.</=
strong></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,5=
5,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;min-width: 10px;"><span>I am pictur=
ing myself, many moons ago, in the last few minutes of many Wall Street int=
erviews, the portion when they ask, &#8220;So what questions do you have fo=
r me?&#8221;, asking dumb questions like &#8220;What&#8217;s your favorite =
part about the culture at Deutsche Bank?&#8221; or something equally stupid=
 because I didn&#8217;t actually care enough. I left finance a few years la=
ter when I realized that I had friends who </span><em>loved </em><span>fina=
nce, and that they would always beat me.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 =
20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;min-width: 10=
px;">Another way of putting that, in the context of questions, is that they=
 actually wanted to answer the question, &#8220;How do you pull money from =
the markets when so many other smart people are competing to do the same th=
ing?&#8221; So when they got put in a room with someone who did that profes=
sionally, they asked hungrier specific questions in order to better answer =
their big question. As Graham wrote, it is very hard to fake what your mind=
 is hungry for.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line=
-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;min-width: 10px;">This is why it is so import=
ant to figure out the big question you&#8217;re trying to answer. Putting y=
ourself in situations that feed your mind what it&#8217;s hungry for lets y=
ou outwork everyone else without even realizing you&#8217;re working. You&#=
8217;re just trying to answer your question!</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;min-width: 10px;=
"><span>Each person&#8217;s mind is hungry for different things (different =
nutritious things, at least), and each person&#8217;s big question will be =
different. There are things that I find absolutely fascinating that possibl=
y only 37 people in the world would care about. Like when I was interviewin=
g Anil and Sunil for the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/d7=
e813df-8338-4300-9378-1956a24f86fe?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);text-dec=
oration: underline;">Deep Dive on Meter</a><span>, I was ravenous for more =
information on how they chose which architecture to bet on and why they &#8=
220;selfishly&#8221; replace all of their hardware whenever they release ne=
w hardware. That was so much fun for me, because one of my sub-questions is=
, &#8220;How can </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/b0913588-0=
0cf-4e26-a2fc-8a5bfef5861a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);text-decoration:=
 underline;">Vertical Integrators</a><span> beat incumbents by building bet=
ter, faster, cheaper products?&#8221; and there were two of the best I&#821=
7;d ever met at doing just that willing to spend their time to help me answ=
er it.</span></p></div></div></div></div><table class=3D"email-ufi-2-bottom=
